# Lists with Sections

Sometimes your data is naturally grouped, e.g., contacts by first letter, or tasks by date. `SectionList` is designed for this.

It works similarly to `FlatList`, but its `data` prop is replaced by `sections`, an array of objects with:

* `title` (optional) – the section header text.
* `data` – an array of items in that section.
* `renderItem` (optional) – can override the list‑level `renderItem`.

## Basic Structure

```jsx
const sections = [
  {
    title: 'Fruits',
    data: ['Apple', 'Banana'],
  },
  {
    title: 'Vegetables',
    data: ['Carrot', 'Lettuce'],
  },
];
```

slides.codeSnippet:
import React from 'react';
import { SectionList, Text, View } from 'react-native';

const contacts = [
  { name: 'Alice' },
  { name: 'Bob' },
  { name: 'Charlie' },
  { name: 'David' },
];

// Group by first letter
const sections = [
  { title: 'A', data: contacts.filter(c => c.name.startsWith('A')) },
  { title: 'B', data: contacts.filter(c => c.name.startsWith('B')) },
  { title: 'C', data: contacts.filter(c => c.name.startsWith('C')) },
  { title: 'D', data: contacts.filter(c => c.name.startsWith('D')) },
];

export default function ContactsList() {
  return (
    <SectionList
      sections={sections}
      keyExtractor={(item, index) => item.name + index}
      renderItem={({ item }) => <Text>{item.name}</Text>}
      renderSectionHeader={({ section: { title } }) => (
        <View style={{ backgroundColor: '#f0f0f0', padding: 5 }}>
          <Text style={{ fontWeight: 'bold' }}>{title}</Text>
        </View>
      )}
    />
  );
}
